The Riemann Hypothesis as a Dynamical Rigidity Problem
Zero Motion, Local Barriers, and Heat-Flow Structure in the de Bruijn–Newman Family

Abstract
--------

We study the motion of real zeros under heat-type deformations associated with the Riemann ξ-function and the de Bruijn–Newman family. Starting from the exact zero-tracking identity

    ṫ_i = - F_λ / F_t (t_i),

we derive the local singular structure of zero motion near simple real zeros. In the repulsive heat-flow convention, neighbouring zeros interact through a leading Hadamard pole term of the form

    ṫ_i = 2 Σ_{j≠i} 1/(t_i - t_j) + E_i,

where E_i denotes the regular external contribution.

Numerical experiments on finite zero windows reveal a robust reduced-flow structure. In the healthy regime the velocity field is well described by a two-mode geometry consisting of a Hadamard repulsion mode and a secondary density-balancing mode. Across 252 tested windows, 230 were classified as strong geometry, 5 as borderline, and 17 as weak. The weak windows were not random: they occurred exactly when the minimum gap satisfied

    g_min / Δ̄ < 0.14.

A force decomposition showed that these weak windows are local-pair dominated: the minimum-gap pair contributes approximately 80% of the velocity norm, while the compressive tail contributes only about 1% of the adjacent-pair term. Local rescaling does not rescue these windows under the correct time-scale transformation, indicating that the weak sector is a genuine local-pair regime rather than a global normalisation artefact.

We then formulate a finite-model barrier theorem. In the reduced repulsive model,

    ṫ_i = 2 Σ_{j≠i} 1/(t_i - t_j),

the neighbouring gap g_i = t_{i+1} - t_i satisfies

    ġ_i = 4/g_i
           - 2g_i Σ_{j≠i,i+1}
             1/(|t_{i+1}-t_j| |t_i-t_j|).

Thus a sufficiently isolated small gap is forced open by the singular adjacent-pair term. More generally, a collapsing cluster of r zeros has internal variance derivative

    V̇_int = 2r(r-1),

so a finite real-zero cluster cannot collapse if the external logarithmic derivative is locally Lipschitz across the cluster.

The remaining analytic problem is therefore reduced to a precise bridge condition: prove that, for the full de Bruijn–Newman zero flow, the external logarithmic derivative remains locally Lipschitz near any hypothetical finite real-zero collision. If this condition holds, real-zero collisions are excluded by the cluster-variance barrier.


1. Setup
--------

Let ξ(s) denote the Riemann xi-function and define

    Ξ(t) = ξ(1/2 + it).

The de Bruijn–Newman family may be written formally as

    Ξ_λ(t) = ∫_0^∞ e^{λx²} Φ(x) cos(tx) dx,

with the heat-type identity

    ∂_λ Ξ_λ(t) = -∂_{tt} Ξ_λ(t),

up to the chosen normalisation convention.

More generally, let F(λ,t) be a real entire function, real-valued on ℝ, analytic in (λ,t), and satisfying a heat-type evolution

    F_λ = κ F_{tt}.

The sign of κ determines whether the induced zero motion is attractive or repulsive. The repulsive direction is the relevant convention for the barrier calculations below.

Let

    t_1(λ) < t_2(λ) < ...

denote real simple zeros of F(λ,·), where such an ordering exists.


2. Exact zero tracking
----------------------

Lemma 2.1 — Zero tracking

If t_i(λ_0) is a simple zero of F(λ_0,·), then there is a unique local C¹ trajectory t_i(λ) such that

    F(λ,t_i(λ)) = 0.

Moreover,

    ṫ_i = - F_λ / F_t (λ,t_i).

Proof.

Differentiate

    F(λ,t_i(λ)) = 0

with respect to λ:

    F_λ + ṫ_i F_t = 0.

Since F_t ≠ 0 at a simple zero,

    ṫ_i = - F_λ / F_t.


3. Local Hadamard pole structure
--------------------------------

Assume F admits a local factorisation near its simple zeros,

    F(t) = e^{H(t)} Π_m (t - t_m),

with H analytic in the local region of interest.

At a simple zero t_i,

    F_{tt}/F_t (t_i)
      =
    2H'(t_i) + 2Σ_{m≠i} 1/(t_i - t_m).

Therefore, for a heat-type evolution F_λ = κF_{tt},

    ṫ_i
      =
    -2κ [ H'(t_i) + Σ_{m≠i} 1/(t_i - t_m) ].

In the repulsive convention, rescale the parameter so that the singular part becomes

    ṫ_i
      =
    2Σ_{m≠i} 1/(t_i - t_m) + E_i,

where E_i denotes the regular external contribution.

This is the formal source of the reduced finite-zero model used in the numerical experiments.


4. Pair-gap equation in the finite reduced model
------------------------------------------------

Consider the finite reduced repulsive model

    ṫ_i = 2Σ_{j≠i} 1/(t_i - t_j).

Let

    g_i = t_{i+1} - t_i.

Then

    ġ_i
      =
    4/g_i
    -
    2g_i Σ_{j≠i,i+1}
    1/(|t_{i+1}-t_j| |t_i-t_j|).

The first term is the singular adjacent-pair repulsion. The second term is the compressive tail from all other zeros.

Thus the finite-model gap law has the form

    ġ_i = 4/g_i - C_i g_i

with

    C_i =
    2Σ_{j≠i,i+1}
    1/(|t_{i+1}-t_j| |t_i-t_j|).

If C_i is locally bounded, then g_i cannot vanish in finite time.


5. Controlled-error pair barrier
--------------------------------

Lemma 5.1 — Pair no-collapse under linear error

Let g(λ)>0 satisfy

    ġ ≥ A/g - K(λ)g,

where A>0, K(λ)≥0, and K∈L¹_loc. Then g cannot reach zero in finite λ-time.

Proof.

Let

    h = g².

Then

    ḣ = 2g ġ ≥ 2A - 2K(λ)h.

So

    ḣ + 2K(λ)h ≥ 2A.

Multiplying by the integrating factor

    μ(λ) = exp( ∫_0^λ 2K(u) du )

gives

    (μh)' ≥ 2Aμ.

Hence

    h(λ)
      ≥
    μ(λ)^(-1) [ h(0) + 2A∫_0^λ μ(s) ds ].

The right-hand side is strictly positive for finite λ. Therefore g(λ)>0, and collision is impossible.


6. Local-minimum barrier in the finite model
--------------------------------------------

Let

    g_min = η Δ̄,

where Δ̄ is the mean gap in the finite window.

Let the second-smallest gap be

    g_second = a Δ̄.

A conservative infinite-tail estimate shows that a sufficient barrier condition is

    η < a.

Equivalently,

    g_min < g_second.

Numerically, across 252 tested finite windows, every minimum gap satisfied this strict local-minimum condition and every minimum gap had

    ġ_min > 0.

For the weak-geometry windows specifically:

    g_min / Δ̄ ≈ 0.109–0.135,

with

    ġ_min ≈ 32.4–37.9.

The adjacent-pair term dominated:

    |tail| / |pair| ≈ 0.0066–0.0157.

Thus the weak windows are not collapse-threat windows. They are strong local reopening cases.


7. Cluster-variance barrier
---------------------------

The pair barrier handles isolated two-zero collisions. A possible remaining failure mode is simultaneous collapse of a cluster of r adjacent zeros.

Let

    x_1 < ... < x_r

be a finite cluster and define

    x̄ = (1/r) Σ_{k=1}^r x_k,

    V = Σ_{k=1}^r (x_k - x̄)².

Assume the cluster evolves by

    ẋ_k =
    2Σ_{ℓ≠k} 1/(x_k - x_ℓ) + E_k.

The internal repulsive part satisfies the exact identity

    V̇_int = 2r(r-1).

Derivation.

Let

    y_k = x_k - x̄.

Then

    Σ_k y_k = 0

and

    V̇ = 2Σ_k y_k ẋ_k.

For the internal repulsive part,

    ẋ_{k,int} =
    2Σ_{ℓ≠k} 1/(x_k - x_ℓ).

Thus

    V̇_int =
    4Σ_k y_k Σ_{ℓ≠k} 1/(x_k - x_ℓ).

Pair the unordered terms k<ℓ. Each pair contributes

    y_k/(x_k-x_ℓ) + y_ℓ/(x_ℓ-x_k)
      =
    (y_k-y_ℓ)/(x_k-x_ℓ)
      =
    1.

There are r(r-1)/2 unordered pairs, so

    V̇_int = 2r(r-1).

Now assume the external field is Lipschitz across the cluster:

    |E_k - E_m| ≤ L|x_k - x_m|.

Then

    |V̇_ext|
      =
    |2Σ_k y_k E_k|
      ≤
    2LV.

Therefore

    V̇ ≥ 2r(r-1) - 2LV.

By the same integrating-factor argument as in Lemma 5.1, V cannot reach zero in finite time.


8. Bridge condition for the full de Bruijn–Newman flow
------------------------------------------------------

The finite-model results suggest the following analytic bridge condition.

Near any hypothetical finite real-zero collision of the de Bruijn–Newman family, suppose the zero motion can be decomposed as

    ẋ_k =
    2Σ_{ℓ∈C,ℓ≠k} 1/(x_k - x_ℓ)
    +
    E_k^ext,

where C is the colliding cluster.

If the external contribution satisfies

    |E_k^ext - E_m^ext| ≤ L|x_k - x_m|

within the cluster, then the cluster-variance barrier prevents collapse.

Thus the remaining analytic problem is:

    Prove local Lipschitz control of the external logarithmic derivative
    near any finite real-zero cluster.

Equivalently, if

    F(t) = e^{H(t)} Π_{ℓ∈C} (t - x_ℓ) G(t),

then the required condition is local boundedness of the second derivative of

    H(t) + log G(t)

across the cluster.

This is the narrowed proof target.


9. Numerical reduced-flow results
---------------------------------

The numerical work examined finite windows of zeros under the reduced repulsive flow

    ṫ_i = 2Σ_{j≠i} 1/(t_i - t_j).

The tested windows covered heights

    T = 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000, 5000, 10000,

with window sizes

    n = 12, 16, 20, 24

and shifts

    -4, ..., +4.

Total windows tested:

    252.


9.1 Geometry tiers
------------------

The geometry classifier gave:

    strong geometry      230
    borderline geometry    5
    weak geometry         17

The strong-geometry windows satisfy high Hadamard alignment, high two-mode capture, and strong singular-value separation.

The weak windows all occurred at T=5000 and were exactly characterised by

    g_min / Δ̄ < 0.14.

The threshold table gave:

    threshold                  TP  FP  FN  TN   precision  recall
    g_min / Δ̄ < 0.14          17   0   0 235      1.000   1.000

Thus weak geometry is exactly the small-gap compression regime in the tested family.


9.2 Force decomposition
-----------------------

For weak windows:

    pairFrac_med = 0.7958,

    local4_med = 0.8294,

    tail/pair_med = 0.0114.

For strong windows:

    pairFrac_med = 0.4169.

The correlation with geometry quality was:

    corr(pairFrac, geometry quality) = -0.8305.

Thus geometry weakens when the dynamics become dominated by one adjacent-pair singularity.


9.3 Local rescaling
-------------------

A local minimum-gap rescaling,

    t̃_i = (t_i - t_k) / g_min,

partially improved the weak windows but did not rescue them under the correct time-scale transformation.

For weak windows:

    S1/S2: 7.586 → 9.041,

    R²: 0.9666 → 0.9800.

But

    0/17

weak windows became strong or borderline under physically scaled local geometry.

Therefore the weak sector is not a global scaling artefact. It is a genuine local-pair dominated regime.


9.4 Closure classification
--------------------------

Earlier apparent closure outliers were separated into regimes:

    stable two-mode closure
    beta-degenerate closure
    geometry failure / weak geometry

In the tested closure scan:

    genuine healthy-regime closure failures = 0.

Bad 2×2 closure fits occurred only when either:

    1. the second coordinate β was nearly degenerate, or
    2. the geometry itself entered the small-gap weak sector.

Thus apparent closure anomalies do not falsify the healthy two-mode regime.


10. Interpretation of the reduced-flow regimes
----------------------------------------------

The reduced finite-zero model exhibits two distinct regimes.


10.1 Healthy distributed regime
-------------------------------

When no gap is extremely compressed, the velocity field is distributed across the window. The flow is well described by a two-mode structure:

    1. Hadamard repulsion mode
    2. density-balancing mode

This is the regime where rank-2 geometry and coefficient closure behave well.


10.2 Small-gap local-pair regime
--------------------------------

When

    g_min / Δ̄ < 0.14,

the flow becomes dominated by the minimum adjacent pair. This weakens the global two-mode geometry but strengthens the local reopening barrier.

The weak geometry therefore does not indicate collapse. It indicates that the local singular pair interaction has become the dominant stabilising mechanism.


11. Relation to complex-zero formation
--------------------------------------

For a real entire family analytic in the deformation parameter, creation or annihilation of a nonreal conjugate pair requires a multiple real zero.

Locally, near a generic double zero,

    F(t,λ)
      =
    U(t,λ) [ (t - t_* - r(λ))² - s(λ) ],

with U nonvanishing.

The zeros have the square-root form

    t_±(λ)
      =
    t_* + r(λ) ± sqrt(s(λ)).

Thus complex escape requires a real-zero collision.

The finite-model and cluster-variance barriers show that, under repulsive Hadamard zero dynamics plus Lipschitz external field, such collisions cannot occur.

The full proof target is therefore not a new numerical search. It is the analytic verification of the external Lipschitz condition for the de Bruijn–Newman zero flow.


12. Relation to the de Bruijn–Newman constant
---------------------------------------------

The de Bruijn–Newman constant Λ marks the transition between real-zero and nonreal-zero behaviour in the de Bruijn–Newman family.

The present programme aims at the direction

    Λ ≤ 0,

by seeking a dynamical obstruction to real-zero collision in the repulsive heat-flow convention.

Newman's theorem gives the opposite inequality,

    Λ ≥ 0.

Thus, if the bridge condition were proved for the full Ξ_λ flow, one would obtain

    Λ = 0.

The finite reduced model does not by itself prove this. It supplies the local barrier structure and identifies the exact analytic condition that must be established.


