14. Conclusion
--------------

The numerical and finite-model results point to a two-regime dynamical structure.

In ordinary windows, zero motion is governed by a stable distributed two-mode geometry. In compressed-gap windows, this geometry weakens, but the dynamics become dominated by the adjacent-pair singularity, forcing the minimum gap to reopen.

Thus the only observed weak sector is not a collapse mechanism. It is a local barrier regime.

The proof route is now sharply reduced. To close the argument for the full de Bruijn–Newman flow, it remains to prove that the external logarithmic derivative contributed by zeros outside a finite colliding cluster is locally Lipschitz across that cluster. If that bridge condition holds, the cluster-variance barrier excludes real-zero collisions, and therefore excludes the local mechanism required for complex-zero creation.
